LOC001_BATHROOM
The bathroom contains an enamelled cast iron bath with claw feet
and a toilet bearing a brass tablet calling it 'The Imperial Avenger'.
A washstand with a marble top and a pedestal washbowl complete
the ensemble. A heavy mahogany door leads back out to the [[green:Upstairs landing]].

LOC002_ORCHARD
The park wall runs along the north boundary, several pear-trees trained
in espalier against the old stone. Bare apple trees stand in rows across
the frozen ground, their branches black against a white sky. A dusting
of snow covers the grass between the trunks, too disturbed by fallen
twigs and animal tracks to preserve any clear footprints. A path east
leads to the [[green:Kitchen garden]], whilst the south opens onto a
[[green:Paved terrace]].

LOC003_KITCHEN_GARDEN
The kitchen garden lies frozen and barren under snow. [[green:Footprints]]
criss-cross the frozen vegetables. The [[green:Orchard]] spreads to the north,
the [[green:Outhouses]] to the east, and the [[green:Kitchen]] door to the
south.

LOC004_OUTHOUSES
A cluster of low brick buildings occupies this corner of the grounds: a
laundry with its copper still cold, a coal store with a dusting of black
dust on the snow outside its door, and a timber pigeon-coop from which
the occasional soft sound emerges. The smell of coal smoke and damp
brick hangs in the cold air. Boot marks cross the snow between the
buildings without settling into any clear pattern. The
[[green:Kitchen garden]] lies west, the [[green:Maze]] to the south.

LOC005_ORNAMENTAL_POND
At the western end of a [[green:Paved terrace]] stands an ornamental
[[green:pond]], its surface frozen and hard. Four stone pedestals around it once
held [[green:marble statues]] - the Four Seasons - but one is missing.
[[green:Footprints]] in the snow circle the pond's edge.

LOC006_TERRACE
This paved terrace extends from the house westward toward an
[[green:Ornamental pond]]. The snow shows a profusion of [[green:footprints]] -
many feet have crossed here. To the north lies the [[green:Orchard]], east
a [[green:french window]] into the [[green:Colonel's Study]], and south the
[[green:West walk]].

LOC007_COLONELS_STUDY
[[green:Colonel Darnley's body]] lies upon a turkish carpet, a [[green:port glass]]
beside it. A [[green:tantalus]] of decanters stands on the table, and a [[green:letter]] rests upon
the writing desk. A [[green:gun rack]] displays sporting
pieces, one notably absent. A [[green:French window]] in the west wall bears
a jagged hole; [[green:shattered]] glass litters the floor. A
[[green:Paved terrace]] lies beyond the window, otherwise doors lead to the
[[green:Hall]] and the [[green:Lounge]].

LOC008_HALL
A heavy oak front door with polished brass fittings stands at one end of
the hall, opening onto the [[green:Main drive]], a [[green:door mat]] at its
foot, damp with recent use. The marble floor extends the length of the
room, reflecting what little winter light finds its way through the fanlight
above the door. The walls carry swords and Civil War pikes, and two suits
of fine [[green:armour]] stand sentinel either side of the staircase. A
glass [[green:display case]] mounted on the wall holds flints and pottery
shards collected from the estate grounds. Doors lead to the
[[green:Dining room]], [[green:Music room]], [[green:Colonel's Study]], and
[[green:Lounge]], or the staircase climbs to the [[green:Upstairs landing]].

LOC009_KITCHEN
Game birds hang from the ceiling in this well-appointed kitchen. On the
sink's draining-board lies a [[green:knife]]. By the outside door stands a
line of [[green:boots]] alongside cleaning brushes and polish.
The cook, [[green:Mildred Goodbody]] stands here overseeing the work.
Doors lead to the [[green:Kitchen garden]], [[green:Butler's pantry]],
and [[green:Dining room]].

LOC010_BUTLERS_PANTRY
A small sitting room with a bed behind a curtain, two temporary
beds have been made up. A small [[green:bookshelf]] holds various volumes.
[[green:Arnold Billingsgate]] tends to his duties. Doors lead to the
[[green:Kitchen]] and [[green:Dining room]].

LOC011_MAZE
Low box hedges, trimmed to chest height, form the walls of this modest
maze on the east side of the house. The hedges are dark and winter-dense,
their surfaces carrying a thin crust of snow along each flat top. The
snow on the paths between them has been scuffed and disturbed - possibly
by several people - but the compressed and broken surface will not yield
clear footprints. The [[green:Outhouses]] lie north, the
[[green:East walk]] west, the [[green:East lawn]] south.

LOC012_WEST_WALK
A gravel path runs clockwise around the house between the snow-covered tennis court
and a bed of withered flowers. [[green:Footprints]] are visible in the snow.
The [[green:Main drive]] lies east, the [[green:Summer house]] south-west, the
[[green:West lawn]] south, and a [[green:Paved terrace]] north.

LOC013_LOUNGE
A three-piece suite dominates this room on a Chinese carpet, scattered with
magazines and novels. Recent family portraits hang on the walls. The fireplace
is carved marble holding the remains of a fire, its mantelpiece bearing an
Indian rosewood box with ivory inlay. [[green:Millicent Darnley]] sits here.
Doors lead to the [[green:Hall]] and the [[green:Colonel's Study]].

LOC014_DINING_ROOM
A fine oak table with William and Mary chairs occupies the centre. A glass
case displays Delft pottery, whilst a sideboard holds a silver wine cooler
and Sevres urns. The fireplace is carved marble, its walls hung with Italian
landscapes. Doors lead to the [[green:Hall]], [[green:Kitchen]],
[[green:Butler's pantry]], [[green:Music room]], and [[green:Billiard room]].

LOC015_MUSIC_ROOM
A [[green:piano]] occupies the centre with a [[green:brass ashtray]] on top.
Several chairs, a music stand, and a large
harp with broken strings complete the room. [[green:Arthur Coniston]] lingers
here. Doors lead to the [[green:Hall]], [[green:Dining room]], and
[[green:Billiard room]].

LOC016_BILLIARD_ROOM
A full-size billiard table commands the centre. A board on the wall records a
recent game. Shelves hold magazines and novels by Conan Doyle and Buchan. Three
[[green:wine glasses]] and an [[green:ashtray]] rest atop the bookcase. Sir
[[green:Redvers Slingsby]] stands here. Doors lead to the [[green:Dining room]]
and [[green:Music room]].

LOC017_DRIVE
From wrought-iron gates, the drive sweeps northward toward stone lions flanking
steps that climb to the [[green:Hall]] door. Paths branch away: clockwise around the
house along snow-covered gravel toward the [[green:West walk]] and [[green:West lawn]],
or anti-clockwise through an avenue of statues along the [[green:East walk]]
towards the distant [[green:Stables]]. The snow reveals a confused tangle of
[[green:footprints]] - boot marks, slipper prints, and shoe tracks criss-crossing
in all directions.

LOC018_EAST_WALK
This gravel path runs east-west across the front of the house, flanked by an
avenue of statues. [[green:Footprints]] mark the snow-covered gravel. The
[[green:Main drive]] lies to the west, a box-hedge [[green:Maze]] to the east,
the [[green:Stables]] to the south, the [[green:East lawn]] and the
[[green:Gamekeeper's Cottage]] to the south-east.

LOC019_SUMMER_HOUSE
A wooden summer house stands on a patch of lawn. Inside are croquet mallets and
hoops, several [[green:cigarette ends]], and a [[green:handkerchief]]. Exits lead
to the [[green:West walk]] and [[green:West lawn]].

LOC020_WEST_LAWN
A broad lawn stretches between the west walk and the drive, planted with
young copper beeches still small enough to seem provisional - an
optimistic planting, their bare winter branches fine as pen-strokes
against the grey sky. The snow covering is largely intact but crossed
by [[green:footprints]] in two or three directions. The
[[green:Main drive]], [[green:West walk]], and [[green:Summer house]] are near.

LOC021_STABLES
The stable block is a handsome structure going gently to seed: loose
slates on the roof, paint flaking from the doors, but the horses
inside well-tended enough. One loose box houses Colonel Darnley's bay
hunter, its breath steaming in the cold air. The other half of the
building has been converted to garage a large Daimler, incongruous
beneath a coating of road dust and a worn tarpaulin. The yard between
the buildings is crossed by [[green:footprints]] and littered with
straw and the dark stains of engine oil. The tack room off the yard
holds saddle and gear for the horse. Access to the [[green:Main drive]],
[[green:East walk]], and [[green:East lawn]] lies beyond the yard gate.

LOC022_EAST_LAWN
An open lawn lies between the stable yard and the gamekeeper's cottage,
sheltered to the north by the box-hedge maze. The snow here is
undisturbed at the margins but broken by [[green:footprints]] crossing
from east to west - boot marks, deep and purposeful. A rook picks at
something in the middle distance and does not bother to fly off.
The [[green:Maze]] lies to the north, the [[green:Stables]] to the west,
the [[green:Gamekeeper's Cottage]] to the east.

LOC023_GAMEKEEPERS_COTTAGE
In the damp shade of chestnut trees stands a gamekeeper's cottage tucked
against the south-east corner. The door stands open. Inside are game items,
two shotguns on the wall, an oil-cloth table, an unmade bed, a slop-stone
sink, and an open fire. [[green:Cigarette ends]] litter the dirty hearth
amongst food scraps and newspapers. [[green:Ronald Mellors]] dwells here.
Paths lead from here onto the [[green:East walk]] and [[green:East lawn]].

LOC024_MILLICENT_BEDROOM
Millicent Darnley's bedroom is decorated to a young lady's taste, with a bed,
wardrobe, dressing table, and small writing table. The surfaces overflow with
small dog ornaments and the walls display pictures of favourite pets. Doors
lead out to the [[green:Upstairs landing]] and [[green:Master bedroom]].

LOC025_LANDING
The landing walls hold fine antlers and animal heads alongside poor portraits
of the Darnley ancestors. Doors lead to the [[green:Bathroom]],
[[green:Millicent's bedroom]], [[green:Morning room]],
[[green:Servants' quarters]], or you could take the stairs down into the
[[green:Hall]].

LOC026_SERVANTS_QUARTERS
A single room with two single beds, a rail for clothes behind a curtain, a wash
stand and chest of drawers. On the chest rest a bundle of [[green:correspondence]]
and framed [[green:photographs]]. A gentleman's country-[[green:suit]] with a [[green:newspaper]]
in the pocket hangs among the dresses, and a [[green:pipe]] rests on the washstand.
The maid, [[green:Norah Bagsby]], is tidying this cramped space. Only a door to the
[[green:Upstairs landing]] provides egress.

LOC027_MASTER_BEDROOM
Colonel and Mrs. Darnley's bedroom is heavily panelled with sporting prints and
a humidor of [[green:cigars]]. A [[green:double bed]], [[green:dressing table]],
[[green:wardrobe]], and trouser press furnish the room. A small bathroom is attached.
Doors lead to the [[green:Upstairs landing]], [[green:Millicent's bedroom]], and
the [[green:Morning room]].

LOC028_MORNING_ROOM
A chintz sofa and occasional table with magazines and books furnish this room.
A [[green:piano]] stands against one wall, whilst a [[green:gramophone]] sits on
a table, surrounded by watercolour bird pictures. [[green:Sarah Darnley]] rests
here. Doors lead to the [[green:Upstairs landing]], [[green:Master bedroom]], and
the [[green:Guest room]].

LOC029_GUEST_ROOM
A guest-room decorated in blue with wardrobe, bed, washstand, and writing-table.
By the bed lies a pair of men's [[green:slippers]], slightly damp and mud-stained.
On the writing table sits a pack of [[green:cigarettes]] - an expensive brand - along
with stationary and pens. The only door leads back into the [[green:Morning room]].

PER101_COLONEL_DARNLEY
Aged 60. The Colonel served in the South African War and
contracted enteric fever which left him feeling debilitated and short-
tempered. He had only a small inheritance but made a fortune on the
stock exchange. He was free with his tips on the market, but didn't
always follow his own recommendations.

P_SARAH_DARNLEY
Colonel Darnley's wife. Aged 27. Fair-haired and beautiful, with the kind of
effortless sophistication that comes from knowing one's own effect on a room.
She wears a morning dress that manages to look elegant despite the
circumstances, though her eyes are shadowed and her composure - whilst
convincing - appears to require some maintenance. She is perhaps twenty years
younger than her husband, and looks it.

P_MILLICENT_DARNLEY
Colonel Darnley's daughter. Aged 23. Well-dressed in a blouse and skirt, rather
plain in feature but with a directness of gaze that more than compensates. There
is a composed, watchful quality about her - she gives the impression of a woman
who generally gets what she wants and has thought carefully about how to get it.
Grief, if she feels it, is kept well in hand.

P_ARTHUR_CONISTON
Millicent Darnley's fiance. Aged 25. Average height, very good looking, and
thoroughly aware of both facts. He dresses fashionably and wears black patent
shoes that seem faintly incongruous in a house where a murder has just occurred.
His manner is open and friendly in the way that practised charm always is - easy
to like, harder to read.

P_REDVERS_SLINGSBY
Friend of the deceased. Aged 52. Very tall and angular, with side-whiskers and a
complexion that suggests either robust outdoor health or a considerable
acquaintance with the decanter. He wears country tweeds and boots and carries
himself with the ill-tempered authority of a man accustomed to having his
opinions treated as facts. He is not taking the present situation well.

P_ARNOLD_BILLINGSGATE
The butler. Aged about 60. Bald, thin, and immaculately turned out in a tail
coat, with the gentlemanly manners and careful neutrality of expression that the
position demands. He wears ordinary men's shoes polished to a mirror finish. Of
all the people in the house he appears the most genuinely distressed by the
Colonel's death, though he would consider any outward display of that distress
to be unprofessional.

P_MILDRED_GOODBODY
The cook. Aged 55. A broad, pleasant-faced woman with cheerful eyes and flour on
her apron, who gives the impression that very little in life has ever quite
managed to get the better of her. She meets your gaze directly and answers
questions without apparent calculation. In a household currently full of people
choosing their words with great care, she is a refreshing exception.

P_NORAH_BAGSBY
The housemaid. Aged 19. A small, pale girl in a maid's uniform who sniffs
occasionally and has the look of someone who would very much rather be somewhere
else. She is not unintelligent, but she is young and nervous and the events of
the night have clearly unsettled her more than she is letting on. She answers
questions readily enough, though her eyes dart toward the door at intervals.

P_RONALD_MELLORS
The gamekeeper. Aged 35. Stocky and dark with black curly hair and the kind of
good looks that owe nothing to grooming or effort. He wears working clothes and
hob-nailed boots and regards you with an expression of settled hostility that
suggests this is simply his default manner rather than evidence of a guilty
conscience - though of course it need not be one or the other. He will not, it
is already clear, be volunteering anything.

OBJ201_POND
Near the centre of the pond the ice is thinner as if it has frozen again
after having been broken. Beneath the ice you can see the missing
marble [[green:statue]] and a [[green:revolver]].

OBJ202_SUNKEN_STATUE
The statue that is beneath the ice is the same as those on the
pedestals. Stuck in a crevice of the statue is the soaked butt of a
[[green:cheroot]].

OBJ203_REVOLVER
The revolver found in the pond is a fine quality weapon with decorative grips.
One bullet has been discharged from it.

OBJ204_STATUES
The statues form a set of four, representing the Four Seasons. They
are of Italian marble and rest on their own weight rather than being
cemented to their plinths. Some strength would be required to move
one.

OBJ205_FOOTPRINTS_POND
Only one set of footprints can be made out in the snow. They are of
flat footed bootprints coming to and from the terrace.

OBJ206_SLIPPERS
The slippers are slightly damp and stained with mud. The mud appears fresh
and is concentrated around the heel and toe areas, as if the wearer had walked
purposefully through wet ground. The slippers are well-made with silk lining,
though the lining is now darkened and stained. They give off a faint smell of
earth and something else - perhaps tobacco smoke.

OBJ207_CIGARETTES
These cigarettes are an expensive brand by Fribourg & Treyer, made in London.
The packet is nearly full, with only a few cigarettes removed. The gold embossed
lettering on the blue packet gleams in the light. The cigarettes themselves are
pure white, tightly rolled, and of excellent quality. As a guest in the house,
Arthur Coniston has left his personal supply in the guest room where he is staying.

OBJ208_KNIFE
This is a kitchen knife used for preparing game. The blade shows signs of recent
use and is stained with blood - quite dry now, darkened
to a dull rust colour. The knife is wickedly sharp and the wooden handle bears
the initials "W.D." burnt into it - presumably a previous owner. It lies on the
draining board amongst other kitchen utensils, seemingly unused since dinner
preparation.

OBJ209_BOOTS
All these boots are polished clean except for a large mud stained pair.

OBJ212_FOOTPRINTS_KG
Both flat footed boot prints and slipper prints can be seen going
between the kitchen and the maze.

OBJ213_BED_MASTER
The Colonel's bed is large and ornate with heavy mahogany posts. The linen sheets
and quilted coverlet on one side have been disturbed - slept in - whilst the other
side remains pristine and undisturbed. Clearly Mrs. Darnley slept here, but the
Colonel did not. A silk nightshirt is carefully folded and placed upon the Colonel's
pillow. On the bedside table sits a small bottle of sleeping draught, the stopper
removed and a spoon beside it, yet the bed itself remains untouched on his side.
Whatever the Colonel was doing last night, sleep in his own bed was not his intention.

OBJ214_WARDROBE
As well as clothes the wardrobe contains a selection of men's and women's [[green:shoes]].
The wardrobe is impressive - made of polished mahogany with ornate brass handles.
Inside hang numerous dresses, petticoats, and undergarments in organised rows.
The men's clothing includes smoking jackets, dinner suits, and country wear. One
suit of country tweeds hangs noticeably alone, somewhat apart from the Colonel's
own garments - it appears to belong to a visitor.

OBJ215_CIGARS
The humidor is mahogany with a glass front, bearing the inscription
"S.D. - 1910" in silver lettering. It contains Burmah cheroots - straight, dark
cylinders, unfashionable compared to the Havanas favoured by gentlemen of means,
but evidently the Colonel's longstanding and unashamed preference. A military
man's smoke: practical, strong, and unpretentious.

OBJ216_DRESSING_TABLE
The dressing table is of polished walnut with a triple mirror and a glass top
beneath which family photographs have been arranged. The surface holds the usual
feminine effects - powder, scent bottles, a hairbrush and comb in silver plate -
all neatly ordered. One scent bottle has been knocked on its side and not
righted, which seems at odds with the general tidiness of the room.

OBJ217_SHOES
This selection of men's and women's shoes ranges from formal evening wear to
practical country footwear. The women's shoes include delicate satin evening
slippers and sturdy walking boots. The men's collection is equally varied. Most
are clean and well-maintained, but one pair of lady's shoes - soft kid leather
with a slight heel - bears fresh, damp, muddy stains around the heel and sole.

OBJ219_CORRESPONDENCE
These letters are all from Mrs. Goodbody's nephew.

OBJ220_PHOTOGRAPHS
These photographs depict Mrs. Goodbody's various ugly relatives.

OBJ221_SUIT
This gentleman's country-suit is apparently Sir Redvers' own garment. It is made
of fine Scotch tweed in a dark green and brown pattern, well-tailored and evidently
expensive. The suit has been carefully hung in the servants' quarters wardrobe,
though this is an odd place for a visitor's good clothing. Why would Sir Redvers
leave his suit here rather than in his guest room? Inside the jacket pocket,
a label reads "Hawes & Curtis, Piccadilly."

OBJ222_NEWSPAPER
One headline on the front page catches your eye -
'Collapse of Rio Plata Mining Co. - Our co-respondent in Lima, Peru
reports the collapse of several silver mining companies through the
fraud of their directors. These frauds are expected to cause heavy
loss to British investors.'

OBJ223_PIPE
The pipe is in the style called 'calabash' with a meerschaum bowl and amber
mouthpiece - a gentleman's smoking pipe of considerable quality and expense. The
bowl still bears the residue of tobacco, now darkened and hardened. The pipe sits
on the servants' quarters washstand, suggesting it belonged to a visitor. The
amber mouthpiece shows signs of much use and is polished smooth by years of
handling.

OBJ224_BOOKSHELF
A modest shelf of books: volumes on household management, domestic accounts, and
the improving literature favoured by the respectable working man. A Bible, much
used. A copy of Smiles's Self-Help with a name written inside the front cover in
careful copperplate - Arnold Billingsgate, 1889. The books tell you rather more
about their owner than he may be willing to tell you himself.

OBJ225_FRENCH_WINDOW_TERRACE
One of the panes is smashed into jagged teeth of glass. There is, however, no
glass on the terrace itself - it has all fallen inward into the study. The
window lock shows that it cannot be locked or unlocked from outside; the
mechanism is internal. The wooden frame shows no signs of tampering or forcing
- the glass has simply been broken from outside, the lock then opened from within.

OBJ226_FOOTPRINTS_TERRACE
A mess of footprints including boots, slippers and some shoe prints.

P_THE_BODY
The body is dressed in a smoking jacket open at the chest. There is a
bloody bullet wound in the front of his dress-shirt. The bullet has not
passed through the body. Evidently the Colonel had got out of his
chair on hearing or seeing his murderer. The impact of the bullet had
caused him to spin and fall and the furniture had got in the way,
further deflecting the body. It is no longer possible to tell the
direction of the shot.

OBJ228_PORT_GLASS
The port glass is one of a set engraved with the words 'Floreat
Darnley'. A crust of dried liquid is at the bottom and lip marks on the
rim though no trace of lipstick.

OBJ229_TANTALUS
The tantalus is made of cherrywood. It holds an empty decanter
with a silver label marked 'Brandy' and a half full decanter marked
'Port'. The decanters are normally inaccessible since they are held in
place by a sort of 'lid' of wood which is fastened by a small lock. The
key is in the lock.

OBJ230_LETTER
The letter is an incomplete draft: "Dear Sir, I have considered your
monstrous suggestion and find I cannot..."

OBJ231_GUN_RACK
This mahogany rack is mounted on the study wall and displays sporting rifles and
revolvers. It is a fine piece of craftsmanship with brass fittings and glass
panels. One pair of decorative revolvers with engraved grips should be present,
but only one remains. The missing revolver has left a clear outline in the felt
backing, showing exactly where it once rested.

OBJ232_FRENCH_WINDOW_STUDY
The study side of this French window bears a jagged hole where one pane has been
smashed. The glass on the floor inside is sprinkled across the carpet and the sill.
No glass lies on the terrace outside - it all fell inward. The hole is roughly
hand-sized, large enough for someone to reach through and manipulate the lock.
The frame is solid mahogany and bears no marks of forcing or violence beyond the
broken pane itself.

OBJ233_SHATTERED_GLASS
This glass is apparently from the smashed French window pane. The shards are sharp
and glittering, some as large as a man's hand, others fine as sand. The glass has
a peculiar property - when examined closely, each shard seems to have fallen
inward. Yet the pattern of breakage is odd; some pieces rest atop others in a
way that suggests the breakage may not have been a single violent impact, but
perhaps more deliberate - possibly even repeated strikes against the pane.

OBJ234_GRAMOPHONE
It has a device for playing several records in sequence. All the
records are Chopin.

OBJ235_PIANO_MORNING
There are several sheets of Schubert Lied music on the piano's music
stand.

OBJ236_DISPLAY_CASE
This glass case is mounted on the hall wall and displays an interesting collection
of archaeological finds. According to a label at the front, these flints and
pottery shards were discovered in the grounds of the estate during excavations some
years ago. The case is kept locked with a small brass key. Inside, carefully
arranged on black velvet, lie hand-axes, arrowheads, and ancient pottery fragments
- the Colonel apparently had an interest in the history beneath his own land.

OBJ237_FOOTPRINTS_WW
There are slipper prints, flat-footed boot prints and some shoe prints
heading to and from the terrace and the front of the house.

OBJ238_CIGAR_STUB
A cheroot stub sits in the brass ashtray on the music room piano - a straight
dark cylinder, partially smoked and carefully stubbed out, the ash still faintly
moist. Someone was in this room recently, smoking.

OBJ239_PIANO_MUSIC
The sheets of music on the piano are for duets.

OBJ240_WINE_GLASSES
The three wine glasses are all dirty, bearing the stains of red wine that has
long since dried. They sit atop the bookcase in the billiard room, clearly forgotten
after last night's game. The glasses are fine crystal, part of a set, with
delicate stems. The wine residue in each glass suggests they were filled and then
left standing - perhaps abandoned hastily?

OBJ241_ASHTRAY
This ashtray rests atop the billiard room bookcase and contains the remains of
three cigars - one Havana and two cheroots. The ash is dark and densely packed,
suggesting these cigars were smoked in succession without pause, and were clenched
hard rather than smoked in a relaxed manner. The Havana is of the finest quality,
yet it has been stubbed out half-smoked. One of the cheroots is charred and blackened
as if it burned intensely before being discarded.

OBJ243_FOOTPRINTS_DRIVE
The prints from flat footed boots go east and west along the gravel
path in front of the house. Slipper prints come from the house and
head east and west along the path. Prints from men's shoes come
from the house and go west. Prints from lady's shoes head to and
from the front door and the west lawn. At the gate end of the drive
the prints from men's hobnailed boots go between the west lawn and
the stables.

OBJ244_FOOTPRINTS_EW
The prints from flat footed boots and men's slippers are visible in the
snow heading around the corner of the house, to and from the maze
and avenue of statues.

OBJ245_CIGARETTE_ENDS_SH
These cigarette ends come from a cheap, mass produced brand. There are
perhaps a dozen of them scattered about the summer house floor, some trodden into
the dust, others carefully arranged. The tobacco inside is coarse and poor quality.
They suggest prolonged occupation of the summer house by someone of modest means
- or someone pretending to be.

OBJ246_HANDKERCHIEF
This is a lady's handkerchief of plain linen with delicate lace edging and a faint
perfume - the scent is floral, sweet, and distinctly expensive. The handkerchief
is initialled with an ornate "M" worked in pale silk thread. It is slightly damp
and bears traces of dirt on one corner, as if it has been clutched in a nervous
hand. The perfume is distinctive - not common, and quite costly.

OBJ247_FOOTPRINTS_WL
Prints from lady's shoes and men's hob-nailed boots can be seen in the
snow going between the drive and the summer house.

OBJ248_FOOTPRINTS_ST
The prints from hob-nailed boots can be seen in the snow going
between the drive and the east lawn.

OBJ249_FOOTPRINTS_EL
The prints from hob-nailed boots can be seen in the snow going east
to west between the stables and the cottage.

OBJ250_CIGARETTE_ENDS_GC
These cigarette ends come from a cheap, mass produced brand.
There are perhaps twenty of them scattered about the cottage hearth amongst food
scraps and newspapers. The tobacco is coarse and cheap. Ronald Mellors
apparently smokes incessantly, and his choice of cigarette reflects his
station.

OBJ251_ARMOUR
Two suits of Civil War three-quarter armour stand to either side of the
staircase, their visors closed. The plate is old but well maintained, the metal
dark and oiled. Someone has polished the breastplates recently - you can see
your own reflection, distorted, staring back at you. They are the kind of thing
that seems merely decorative in daylight and considerably less so after dark.

OBJ252_DOOR_MAT
The doormat is made of coarse coir and bears the word 'WELCOME' in faded letters.
It is decidedly damp with recent use, the moisture having soaked through to the
wooden floor beneath it. The dampness is concentrated at the edges and corners
where water might drip from wet boots or shoes. There are distinct muddy footprints
impressed into the coir - at least two sets, one noticeably smaller than the other.
The mat has not yet dried, suggesting the wet footprints are fresh - from last night
or early this morning.

OBJ253_CHEROOT_BUTT
This is the sodden butt of a Burmah cheroot, waterlogged from its time in
the pond. Despite being soaked, you can still make out its straight dark
cylinder shape, characteristic of a cheroot rather than a conventional
cigarette. It was wedged in a crevice of the statue as if placed there
deliberately or dropped in haste.

OBJ254_MUSIC_ROOM_ASHTRAY
This brass ashtray of considerable quality sits on the piano. It contains a single
cigar stub - a cheroot by the appearance - partially smoked and carefully stubbed
out. The cigar bears the tooth marks of someone who smoked it clenched between their
teeth. Beside the stub lies a small pile of ash. The stub is the only evidence of
smoking in this room, yet someone claims to have smoked here recently. Odd.

WHAT_REALLY_HAPPENED
What really happened at Darnley Park?@
@
On the morning of the murder Arthur Coniston, the boy-friend of
Millicent Darnley, arrived by arrangement to ask Colonel Darnley for
permission to marry his daughter. This conversation took place
during the afternoon and Colonel Darnley refused the request.
Although he found Coniston amusing, he felt that his visitor was
after Millicent's inheritance. Coniston, now resolved upon murder,
quietly informing the other members of the household that the
Colonel had agreed to the marriage. He was unaware that the Colonel
had decided to write him a letter confirming his rejection. During the
afternoon an unexpected visitor arrived, Sir Redvers Slingsby who
had invested in Peruvian mining shares on the advice of his friend
Colonel Darnley. In the morning's papers was news of the collapse of
these shares. Angry with his friend, Slingsby had rushed down to
Darnley Park to ask the Colonel to lend him money to avoid ruin.@
@
Dinner that evening finished at 9.00. Millicent and Sarah retired
to the lounge for coffee while the men drank port and played
billiards. At 9.30 the gentlemen joined the ladies while the
servants ate in the kitchen. The atmosphere was tense since
Slingsby had not had opportunity to raise his problems. At 10.00 that
night impatience got the better of him and he drew Darnley to the
study whilst Coniston and Millicent went to the music room to sing
duets. For half an hour Slingsby and the Colonel quarrelled (at this
time Billingsgate was cleaning boots in the kitchen) and at 10.30
Slingsby stormed out of the study by the hall door, slamming it
furiously. This noise was interpreted by some as a shot. The
slamming of the door underlined the generally tense atmosphere.
The ladies went upstairs but Arthur Coniston stayed in the music
room smoking a cheroot and considering his plan. He was unaware
that Sarah had plans of her own.@
@
Sarah Darnley was unhappy with her husband and having an
affair with Mellors, the gamekeeper. She had arranged to meet
Mellors at the summer house at 10.45. Mellors was there, waiting and
smoking cigarettes. Sarah took steps to keep the affair secret and to
maintain to Millicent the pretence that she was in the house, she told
her of her intention to play on the morning room piano. In truth she
played a series of gramophone records which Millicent heard from her
room. It was not necessary for her to take account of Colonel Darnley
since experience had taught her that the Colonel would lock himself
in his study and get drunk on such an occasion as this. Sarah next
left the house and went down to the summer house where she met
Mellors.@
@
Leaving the music room, Coniston tried the study door and finding
it locked, guessed what was happening and devised his plan. He had
stolen a gun from the study earlier in the day. He now changed into
dressing gown and slippers and went outside the house and around to
the kitchen door which was open. Reaching through the door he
picked up Sir Redvers Slingsby's boots. Changing into them he walked
around the house to the terrace. The boots being too large, they left
flat-footed bootprints. From the terrace Coniston looked into the
study where the Colonel was drinking. He tapped on the window, the
Colonel stood up and saw him, Coniston fired the gun and the Colonel
fell dead. He now had to act fast to dispose of the gun, disguise of the
fact of the bullet-hole in the window glass and return the boots. He
broke the ice on the pond with a statue taken from one of the
pedestals and threw the gun into the water. He then returned to the
kitchen, changed the boots for the slippers and then entered the
house by the front door. He did not notice Sarah who had heard the
shot and rushed back before everyone was roused by the noise and
she was discovered. In her haste Sarah dropped a handkerchief in
the summer house.@
@
Coniston now came to the boldest part of his plot. He woke
Billingsgate and persuaded him to break in by the French window
instead of searching for his keys. Coniston took care to reach the
patio before his companion and threw a stone through the same pane
of glass that bore the bullet-hole from the fatal shot, thus
obliterating the evidence of where the shooting took place. He
then invited Billingsgate to open the window and confirm that it had
been locked. He also told the Butler that he intended to follow the
murderer's bootprints which were clear in the snow. The object of
this move was to provide an explanation of the trail already left by
his slippers when he first stole and returned the boots.@
@
Various minor clues led towards Coniston as the murderer, but one
was fatal to him. It was evident that the murderer had worn the
boots and returned them to the kitchen. How then had the murderer
left the kitchen in his or her own footwear? There were only two
possibilities : the murderer had left via the butler's pantry or the
outside door. The former was impossible since three people were
occupying the pantry of whom at least one (Mrs. Goodbody) had been
wakened by the shot and would have heard any stranger entering the
room. The second was possible but the murderer would leave the foot-
prints of his ordinary footwear. Other than the boots, there were
prints only from Arthur Coniston's slippers. Coniston's explanation
that he had left these prints in following the murderers boot-trail
would not hold water. The murderer had to leave footprints in two
sets of footwear. Coniston's slippers were the only other set.

SEALED_ROOM_INTRO
[[green:The Sealed Room Murder]]@
@
You have been summoned to Darnley Park one winter's day to
investigate the murder of Colonel Sebastian Darnley at some time
the previous evening.@
@
The suspects are:@
@
  [[green:Sarah Darnley]]        - the deceased's wife@
  [[green:Millicent Darnley]]    - the deceased's daughter@
  [[green:Arthur Coniston]]      - fiance of Millicent@
  [[green:Sir Redvers Slingsby]] - friend of the deceased@
  [[green:Arnold Billingsgate]]  - butler@
  [[green:Mildred Goodbody]]     - cook@
  [[green:Norah Bagsby]]         - housemaid@
  [[green:Ronald Mellors]]       - gamekeeper@
@
You are free to search the house and grounds and to question the
suspects. Examination of the scene and skillful interrogation will
yield sufficient information to solve the mystery. And mystery it is!
The body of Colonel Darnley was found in his study, the doors and
window of which were all locked from the inside. The only keys were
in the possession of the Colonel and his faithful butler.@
@
[[green:How could the sealed-room murder be committed?]]

